\[
\textbf{Counterexample:} \text{ Let } n = 122 \text{, so } \sqrt{122} \approx 11.045. \text{ The primes } p < \sqrt{122} \text{ are } 2,\,3,\,5,\,7,\,11. \text{ Noting that } 122-2=120,\;122-3=119,\;122-5=117,\;122-7=115,\;122-11=111 \text{ are all composite, we conclude that the statement is false.}
\]

\[
\textbf{Since } n = 122 \text{ provides a counterexample (with } \sqrt{122} \approx 11.045 \text{ and for each prime } p \in \{2,3,5,7,11\},\, 122-p \text{ is composite), the statement is false.}
\]
